      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Here's an interesting profile of one of the most successful Substack authors:",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "type": "bookmark",
        "url": "https://www.nytimes.com/2020/12/27/business/media/heather-cox-richardson-substack-boston-college.html",
        "metadata": {
          "url": "https://www.nytimes.com/2020/12/27/business/media/heather-cox-richardson-substack-boston-college.html",
          "title": "Heather Cox Richardson Offers a Break From the Media Maelstrom. It’s Working.",
          "description": "She is the breakout star of the newsletter platform Substack, doing the opposite of most media as she calmly situates the news of the day in the long sweep of American history.",
          "author": null,
          "publisher": "NYTimes",
          "thumbnail": "https://static01.nyt.com/images/2020/12/29/us/27bensmith-print/27bensmith-print-facebookJumbo-v2.jpg",
          "icon": "https://www.nytimes.com/vi-assets/static-assets/apple-touch-icon-28865b72953380a40aa43318108876cb.png"
        }
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The thing it catches, I think, is that the big successes are often doing new things with the medium, rather than ramming old wine into new bottles.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Responsible reporting on the vaccines",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "koenig-heading",
        "tag": "h2",
        "version": 1,
        "renderVersion": "3.0"
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "We're in a weird stage with the pandemic: while the beginning of the end is most likely here with multiple vaccines entering circulation, there's still plenty that could go wrong. And it's possible that the next two months might be the bleakest of the COVID19 crisis. ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Vaccination is our best way out — but misinformation is circulating, both intentional and accidental, from non-specialist reporters getting their facts wrong. This piece is a good starting point on getting them right.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "type": "bookmark",
        "url": "https://ijnet.org/en/story/tips-journalists-reporting-covid-19-vaccines",
        "metadata": {
          "url": "https://ijnet.org/en/story/tips-journalists-reporting-covid-19-vaccines",
          "title": "Tips for journalists reporting on COVID-19 vaccines",
          "description": "As the world awaits an effective coronavirus vaccine, reporters covering the story face a daunting task: separating fact from fiction. Or, as veteran health care journalist Gary Schwitzer describes it, navigating the “perfect storm of pandemic misinformation.”",
          "author": "Sherry Ricchiardi",
          "publisher": "International Journalists' Network",
          "thumbnail": "https://ijnet.org/sites/default/files/styles/share_2_1/public/story/2020-12/markus-spiske-DnBtFBnqlRc-unsplash.jpg?h=b0c9c7ef&itok=qR6-GO7r",
          "icon": "https://ijnet.org/sites/default/files/favicons/apple-touch-icon.png"
        }
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Never Trust Facebook",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "koenig-heading",
        "tag": "h2",
        "version": 1,
        "renderVersion": "3.0"
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "For the last decade or so, I've maintained that Facebook is a fundamentally untrustworthy company. I'm not just talking about the healthy cynicism all journalists should maintain about companies, but about the very fundamentals of the social network company's culture being self-serving and hostile to others.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "This excellent piece of work by the Bureau of Investigative Journalism is just more fuel for the fire:",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
